sections.Biography:
===Background===
He was once [[Lord of Casterly Rock]] and head of [[House Lannister]], one of the [[Great Houses]] of [[Westeros]]. The Lannisters are the richest and one of the most influential families in Westeros. He is the father of [[Tywin Lannister]], and grandfather of [[Cersei Lannister|Cersei]], [[Jaime Lannister|Jaime]], and [[Tyrion Lannister|Tyrion]].&lt;ref name=&quot;House Lannister viewers guide&quot;&gt;[http://viewers-guide.hbo.com/game-of-thrones/season2/#!/guide/houses/lannister/ HBO viewers guide, season 2 guide to houses, House Lannister entry]&lt;/ref&gt;

Lord Tytos raised the kennelmaster of Casterly Rock to knighthood after the latter saved him from a [[Lions|lioness]] that tried to kill him. He also granted him lands, a keep, and the kennelmaster's son was taken as a squire. Thus [[House Clegane]] was born.&lt;ref&gt;&quot;[[House Clegane (Histories &amp; Lore)]]&quot;&lt;/ref&gt;

Tytos presided over a period of decline for the House. He frittered away much of their fortune on poor investments and allowed himself to be mocked at court creating a perception of weakness.

This reputation led the Lannister vassals of [[House Reyne]] of [[Castamere]] to eventually rise in [[Reyne Rebellion|rebellion]]. Tytos' successor, Tywin, put down the rebellion personally, extinguishing their house and re-establishing the fearsome reputation of House Lannister. His ruthlessness gave darker meaning to the common phrase &quot;A Lannister always pays his debts&quot; and was immortalized in the song &quot;[[The Rains of Castamere (song)|The Rains of Castamere]]&quot;.&lt;ref&gt;&quot;[[House Lannister (Complete Guide to Westeros)]]&quot;&lt;/ref&gt;

===[[Season 1]]===
When arriving at his father's encampment with a number of [[Hill tribes|hill tribe]] leaders, [[Tyrion Lannister]] introduces his father to them, calling him &quot;Tywin, son of Tytos&quot;.&lt;ref&gt;&quot;[[The Pointy End]]&quot;&lt;/ref&gt;

===[[Season 2]]===
At [[Harrenhal]], Tywin recalls watching Tytos growing old to [[Arya Stark|his cup-bearer]]. Tywin believes that his father loved him and was a good man but weak. He blames Tytos for endangering their house and name.&lt;ref&gt;&quot;[[The Old Gods and the New]]&quot;&lt;/ref&gt;
